<HEADLINE>
<P>
KIDS AT MOVIES (CONT.) 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
After reading Dr. Joseph Herman's Dec. 10 letter criticizing Barbara Marcus' 
desire to restrict children under the age of 5 from movie theaters, I strongly 
regret that he wasn't sitting next to me last Saturday evening as a 3-year-old 
boy in front of me talked throughout the entire funeral scene of "Steel 
Magnolias." Then he, too, could have had the climax scene of the film 
completely ruined. 
</P>
<P>
As an early-childhood education teacher, I know the limits of young children. I 
think it's cruel for parents to expect their toddlers to sit quietly and still 
for two hours at a movie that holds no interest for them. 
</P>
<P>
If we cannot restrict toddlers from movies, maybe the theaters could take a 
lesson from restaurants ("smoking" and "non-smoking") and offer seating in 
"talking" and "non-talking" sections. 
</P>
<P>
SETH E. CUTLER 
</P>
<P>
Glendale 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA123189-0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 155614 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
December 31, 1989, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
