<HEADLINE>
<P>
ABOUT THE TOP MOVIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
While including on their Top 10 lists for the 1980s voyeuristic sleaze ("Blue 
Velvet"), hip amateurism ("Do the Right Thing"), childish trivia ("Raiders of 
the Lost Ark") and pretentious pseudo art ("Raging Bull"), the Times' movie 
reviewers revealed the prerequisites for their job: short memories and bad 
taste. 
</P>
<P>
Conspicuous by their absence were such clearly superior works as "Breaker 
Morant," "The Flight of the Eagle," "The Official Story," "When Father Was Away 
on Business," "A Cry in the Dark," "Melvin and Howard" and "Diner." 
</P>
<P>
Even Peter Rainer included on his list "E.T." -- which may have been fun, but 
let's not raise calculating box-office movie candy to the level of films with 
genuine substance, originality and lasting merit. 
</P>
<P>
DOUGLAS CARASSO 
</P>
<P>
Whittier 
</P>
