A 1989 RETROSPECTIVE; 
</P>
<P>
HEROES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
When his mother began to choke on a lozenge in their Van Nuys condominium, 
3-year-old Jameson Rodgers remembered what his parents had trained him to do. 
He dialed 911. "My mom's on the floor. She can't breathe," the tot told a Fire 
Department dispatcher in a calm, articulate voice. Minutes later, paramedics 
arrived and found Peggy Rodgers on her hands and knees, on the verge of 
unconsciousness. After two tries, they managed to dislodge the lozenge. Leonard 
Washington of Pomona reacted decisively when he noticed a group of black-booted 
"skinheads" accosting a Middle Eastern family in a La Verne parking lot. 
Washington, 34, stopped his car and proceeded to hold off the quartet of 
attackers, one of whom had menacingly waved a baseball bat, until police 
arrived. Nineteen other heroes received awards ranging from $250 to $10,388 
from the county Board of Supervisors for their roles in bringing Night Stalker 
Richard Ramirez to justice. "It was my biggest experience, to know that I 
confronted him face-to-face and knew that it was him," said Edgardo Molinar of 
Covina, who helped chase Ramirez through East Los Angeles on the day of his 
capture in August, 1985. 
</P>
