</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
VIDEO DISKS; LASERS; COLLECTIONS; MOTION PICTURES 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA123189-0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 155722 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
December 31, 1989, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Calendar; Page 7; Calendar Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
2049 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
ZAP! INTO THE NINETIES; 
</P>
<P>
STATE OF THE ART FOR FILMS; 
</P>
<P>
THE LASER VIDEO DISC WILL DO TO HOME ENTERTAINMENT IN THE NEXT DECADE WHAT THE 
VCR DID IN THE EIGHTIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JACK MATHEWS, Jack Mathews, film editor of The Times, assesses the software 
situation in the laser-disc market and offers tips for starting a home movie 
library. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ten years ago, when America was saying goodby to the decade that bred both 
Watergate and the pet rock, the film and electronics industries were fresh 
allies on the brink of the biggest home entertainment revolution since the 
invention of television. 
</P>
<P>
Now, as we say goodby to the decade that bred Contragate and designer water, 
they are inching toward the brink again. Having spoiled us rotten with 
cost-efficient VCRs, neighborhood video stores and $2 movie rentals,the 
Hollywood and Tokyo-based partners are about to lead us out of the Fuzzy Age of 
videotape and into the 425-lines-of-resolution, four-channel digital audio age 
of the video disc. 
</P>
<P>
In the 1980s, we got used to watching movies cheaply at home, at our 
convenience, without commercial interruptions. In the 1990s, we will get used 
to watching them under conditions that will almost duplicate the experience in 
first-run theaters. That means we will switch to larger, higher-definition 
screen TV sets and, most likely, to laser video-disc players. 
</P>
<P>
The thousands of techologically hip who have already installed video-disc 
players at home have long known the advantages of discs over tape, not only for 
viewing movies but for filmed concerts, interactive lectures and for film 
study, as well. Laser delivers vastly sharper images and crisper, fuller sound, 
but the album-size discs can also be encoded to show both motion and still 
pictures, and though the discs themselves are more expensive to manufacture and 
encode than videotape cassettes, they never wear out. 
</P>
<P>
"A lot of this I don't understand, but what I do understand is (we're building) 
a knowledgeable movie audience," said former Academy of Motion Pictures Arts 
and Sciences president Fay Kanin, at a recent event where film cinematographers 
gathered for a demonstration of video-disc technology. "I remember the first 
time I went out to a video store . . . and saw those rows of films and the 
people's excitement, I really thought the millenium had come. You're now 
educating a public to understand what (movies) are all about." 
</P>
<P>
Movies -- first threatened with obsolescence by radio, then TV, then home video 
-- are stronger than ever as we enter the last decade of the first electronic 
century, and whatever the 1990s bring, they will likely be stronger in the year 
2000. Japanese electronics giant Sony closed out the '80s with its purchase of 
Columbia Pictures, and other foreign buyers -- more from the Land of the Rising 
Sun, to be sure -- will follow. 
</P>
<P>
The "Made in Japan" label that used to serve as a warning sign on tinny 
5-and-dime gadgets is now a boast of excellence on robot-assembled automotive 
and electronics goods. Having captured the bulk of the hardware market in the 
still growing home electronics industry, the Japanese's next frontier for 
expansion is here, in Hollywood, where -- despite a measurable slide in quality 
control -- the "Made in the U.S.A." label still means something. 
</P>
<P>
The colorizing of black-and-white classic movies provided one of the 1980s' 
hottest technological controversies, but that aesthetic felony, along with the 
equally crass mayhem done on wide-screen films to make them fit the nearly 
square TV format, will be forgotten like bad wine once wide-screen, 
high-resolution TV is here. 
</P>
<P>
Sony executives, in the afterglow of their purchase of Columbia Pictures, talk 
about the future they see for Sony's high-definition video technology for film 
production. By shooting and editing movies on videotape then transferring the 
final version to film, they say production costs can be drastically reduced. 
This is true, especially with films laden with expensive special effects, but 
will anybody want to see the movies? 
</P>
<P>
In the few instances where the tape-to-film process has already been used -- in 
the Kathleen Turner film "Julia and Julia," for instance -- audiences thought 
they were watching a TV soap opera in a theater. Most front-rank film directors 
wouldn't touch tape with a 10-foot boom pole. 
</P>
<P>
"The Sony people are deluding themselves into thinking video will ever replace 
film," said director Joe Dante ("Gremlins"), a keen follower of cutting-edge 
film technology. "I can't believe that outside porno theaters, audiences will 
accept that kind of quality." 
</P>
<P>
Does that mean film and film projectors will still be the way movies are shown 
in theaters 10 years from now? Possibly. The 35-millimeter, 
24-frames-per-second system of filming and projection has been the standard for 
about 70 years. There have been occasional technological forays into theatrical 
exotica: 3-D, Cinemascope, Cinerama, 70-mm, Imax, Showscan (70-mm shot at 60 
frames per second). But the real adventures ahead are, as they were in the 
'80s, more likely to occur at home than in the multiplex. 
</P>
<P>
People with large screens, video-disc players and proper surround-sound audio 
systems have already glimpsed and heard the future and even with the current 
limitations, it looks bright and sounds clear. Such wide-screen films as 
"Lawrence of Arabia" and "The Robe" are already available on video disc in 
their original full frame format. The "letterboxed" discs create a black band 
above and below the film's image, a distraction that American marketing mavens 
believe will cause resistance among consumers here. 
</P>
<P>
As the Japanese gain a greater say in the software sold in the U.S., they may 
be less daunted by that problem. In their country, the video-disc player and 
letterboxed movies are in wider use than squared films on videotape. If the 
future of home entertainment is movies (let's be optimistic and assume the 
future isn't "Married . . . With Children"), it is inevitable that the coming 
high-definition changeover will also bring with it a wider TV screen. After 
all, the square screen only became the standard because when TV was invented, 
movies were square. 
</P>
<P>
In any case, the video-disc player is apt to become the TV accessory of choice 
in the next few years, and in fact, the revolution has already begun. More than 
4,000 films have been transferred to laser discs, disc players are now 
competitively priced with VCRs, and in a growing number of instances, video 
discs offer features that videotape engineers can only dream of. 
</P>
<P>
Santa Monica-based Voyager Company, through its inspired Criterion Collection, 
has been letterboxing wide-screen films for several years. Some of the major 
studios are now doing it, as well. 
</P>
<P>
For knowledgeable movie fans, a group whose size has multiplied with the advent 
of home video, the Criterion discs are a revelation. Such classic films as 
"Singin' in the Rain" and "Citizen Kane" become both perfect-presentation 
movies and annotated film courses. You can watch "Singin' in the Rain" in all 
its Technicolor glory with its original sound track, or you can flip a switch 
on your remote control and have Ron Haver, film curator for the Los Angeles 
County Museum of Art, explain how each scene was shot, who dubbed whose voices, 
and how the film got made in the first place. 
</P>
<P>
At the end of each Criterion release, you get an assortment of ancillary sights 
and sounds. For "The Magnificent Ambersons," the followup to "Citizen Kane" 
that was taken away from Orson Welles and re-redited by RKO, you can not only 
read the original script and note the studio debauchery, but listen to Welles' 
"Mercury Theatre" radio play that inspired the movie. 
</P>
<P>
The supplementary material often includes illustrated story boards (you can see 
how Alfred Hitchcock carefully blocked out the famous crop duster scene for 
"North by Northwest"), still photos, trailers, star and director interviews, 
and scenes that do not appear in the film, either because there wasn't room (a 
Scarecrow and Dorothy number from "The Wizard of Oz," for instance) or because 
there were miscues when shot (there's a painful shot of a stuntman leaping from 
a trolley and landing on his rear end on a paved street for a scene in "Singin' 
in the Rain"). 
</P>
<P>
While our homes are being converted from tape to disc, school rooms and lecture 
halls will get theirs, too. The laser player, projecting from discs that can 
hold more than 100,000 instantly retrievable still photo images, is going to 
make the slide projector seem about as current as a washboard. 
</P>
<P>
Entire museums of art can be put on one disc, indexed and selectively projected 
onto screens. Encyclopaedia Brittanica has transferred more than 100 of its 
educational films to disc and other publishers are moving quickly to create a 
software inventory for the hardware explosion that, with the sudden drop in 
prices, seems inevitable. 
</P>
<P>
Until this year, the cost of quality laser video-disc players has remained high 
compared to VCRs. Now, players equipped with digital stereo sound and capable 
of playing both standard and extended play discs are priced under $500. Since 
the same machines also play all sizes of compact disc recordings, it is cheaper 
to upgrade a home entertainment system with a combination laser video and 
compact-disc player than to buy a compact-disc player and VCR. For about $250 
more, you can add equipment that will make your player interactive, meaning 
that you can buy the indexed three-disc set of "The Louvre," and with a push of 
a button, call up any of the 6,000 pieces of art transferred from the famed 
Paris museum. 
</P>
<P>
According to industry sources, there are between 500,000 and one million 
video-disc players in U.S. households, a fraction of the estimated 60 million 
VCRs in use. The number of films available on disc has lagged way behind those 
on tape, but the presses are busy now. Almost all new films are transferred to 
disc and many of the classic films are getting the kind of specialized 
treatment -- the letterboxing, narration and supplemental material -- for which 
Voyager's Criterion has become known. 
</P>
<P>
The prices of discs are coming down, too. Movies on discs sell for from $25 to 
$40 (Criterion's extended treatment discs go for as much as $125) and in major 
markets like Los Angeles and New York, are readily available for daily rental 
at rates comparable to those charged for tapes. 
</P>
<P>
It is ironic that most of the technology for video-disc players has been around 
almost as long as the VCR. Video-disc players were being demonstrated at 
consumer electronics shows in the late '70s, in the next booth over from tape 
demos. The images and sounds were better even then, but eccentricities in both 
the market and some of the equipment combined to give video a 10-year public 
relations setback. 
</P>
<P>
The most heavily marketed early disc player was RCA's Selectivision, a machine 
that used a needle and turntable to mimic conventional record players. Besides 
the video confusion this caused whenever the family dog leaned against the 
stereo cabinet and attempted to dislodge a flea, the discs seemed fragile and 
distractingly mysterious. 
</P>
<P>
It was also assumed that the greatest use of home video would be to record 
television shows for later viewing. Few people besides those who got rich on it 
foresaw the day when the sales of movies on videotape would exceed box-office 
grosses for first-run movies (home video revenues passed theatrical's in the 
mid-'80s). 
</P>
<P>
Finally, most Americans were satisfied with the relatively poor quality of 
their TV images, and they hadn't even thought of how much better movies would 
sound if the tracks were pumped through their amplifiers and stereo speakers 
instead of being strained through the three-inch mufflers that came with their 
sets. 
</P>
<P>
The remaining drawback to the laser player is its inability to record broadcast 
and cable signals. But even that objection can be over-ruled. Most people who 
move up to disc already have VCRs, and home entertainment systems can 
accomodate both machines. Industry experts say that the need for a machine that 
both records and plays will be met sometime in the '90s, either with the 
introduction of recordable discs (the technology exists, but the price is now 
prohibitive) or with a laser player that includes an 8-millimeter videocassette 
component. 
</P>
<P>
In any event, the logical next step for millions of consumers who have gone 
from being captives of network schedules to having discretionary choice over 
thousands of home entertainment options is to enhance the quality of their 
experience. 
</P>
<P>
 Steven Smith and Nina J. Easton contributed to this story. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
